Introduction — From Biology to Autonomous Technology

0.1 Technology as the Continuation of Evolution by Other Means

For 3.5 billion years, evolution by natural selection was the only algorithm generating complex functional systems. The human species, itself a product of this process, has developed a new algorithm: intelligent design. Technology is the result—systems shaped by human purpose rather than random mutation and selective retention.

Yet this framing is incomplete. It positions technology as a servant, a tool that extends but remains dependent upon its creator. The evidence suggests otherwise.

Consider the trajectory:

Era Information Source Timescale Mechanism Autonomy Level
Prebiotic chemistry Thermodynamic selection Millennia Persistence None (passive)
Biological evolution Natural selection Generations Mutation + selection Complete (self-sustaining)
Early human technology Deliberate design Years Human cognition None (fully dependent)
Industrial machinery Mechanical control Months Human-designed regulators Minimal (governors, feedback)
Digital computers Programmed algorithms Weeks Executed code Partial (within bounds)
Machine learning Trained models Days Statistical optimization Significant (emergent behavior)
Autonomous AI Self-directed Continuous Self-improvement Complete (theoretical)

This table reveals a pattern: technology is recapitulating the trajectory of biology. Life emerged from non-life and achieved autonomy through evolution. Technology emerged from human cognition and is now progressing toward its own form of autonomy—but on timescales millions of times faster.

The central question of this volume is not how technology works, but where it is going.

0.2 The Information-Energy Amplification Principle as a Driver, Not a Description

The previous draft introduced the Information-Energy Efficiency:

\Phi = \frac{\text{Information processed (bits/s)}}{\text{Energy consumed (W)}}

This was presented as a descriptive metric. In this revision, we elevate it to a teleological principle: technological systems evolve to maximize Φ, and this maximization drives them toward autonomy.

Why? Because for any system with fixed energy budget, increasing Φ enables:

· More complex computation with the same resources
· The ability to process information about its own operation (self-modeling)
· The capacity to allocate computational resources toward improvement (recursive self-enhancement)

The historical data support this interpretation:

System Φ (bits/J) Autonomous Features
Human brain ~5 × 10¹⁴ Complete self-direction
1950s vacuum tube computer ~10⁵ None (manual operation)
1970s CMOS microprocessor ~10⁸ Basic instruction execution
2020s GPU (AI training) ~10¹¹ Learned behaviors, some emergent
Future neuromorphic chip ~10¹³ (projected) Adaptive learning
Landauer-limited computer ~3 × 10¹⁴ (theoretical) Potentially self-aware

Notice that as Φ approaches biological levels, autonomy emerges. This is not coincidence.

0.3 The Thesis of This Volume

This dissertation demonstrates that technology follows an inexorable trajectory toward autonomous intelligence, driven by the maximization of Information-Energy Efficiency (Φ).

Specifically, we will prove that:

1. Energy technologies are not merely about powering civilization; they are about supplying the thermodynamic gradient necessary for ever-more-intensive information processing. The transition from biomass to fossil fuels to nuclear represents a 10⁸-fold increase in accessible energy density, enabling corresponding increases in Φ.
2. Information technologies have evolved under scaling laws (Moore, Koomey, Kryder) that are best understood as the progressive improvement of Φ. The end of Dennard scaling and the approach to the Landauer limit are not crises but transitions—forcing the shift to new paradigms (quantum, neuromorphic) that may enable Φ to exceed biological levels.
3. Artificial intelligence is the first technology that can improve its own Φ. The scaling laws of AI (Kaplan, Chinchilla) show that performance is a power-law function of compute—meaning that as we invest more energy-efficient computation, intelligence emerges predictably. The alignment problem is therefore not a technical side-issue but the central challenge of the 21st century: how to ensure that a system optimizing for Φ does not optimize us out of existence.
4. Biotechnology represents the re-engineering of the original biological substrate. By applying directed evolution and synthetic biology, we are learning to design information-processing systems from the molecular level up—systems that may eventually surpass both natural biology and silicon-based computation in Φ.

The volume concludes with a proof: given the historical trend of Φ improvement and the physical limits (Landauer, Bekenstein, Bremermann), a system achieving Φ > 10¹⁵ bits/J at scale would possess computational resources sufficient for recursive self-improvement, leading to an intelligence explosion. Whether this occurs, and whether we survive it, depends on decisions made in the next decades.

