Chapter 5 — Thermal Engines: Converting Heat to Work and Information

5.1 The Primacy of Heat Engines

Despite the diversity of modern energy technologies, the majority of the world's electricity (approximately 80%) is still generated by heat engines—devices that convert thermal energy into mechanical work, which then drives generators. Understanding their fundamental limits is essential for assessing civilization's energy future.

The central fact of heat engines is the Carnot limit:

\eta_{\text{Carnot}} = 1 - \frac{T_C}{T_H}

This is not an engineering constraint but a law of physics. No heat engine operating between two reservoirs can exceed this efficiency, regardless of design. The only way to improve efficiency is to increase $T_H$ (hotter heat source) or decrease $T_C$ (colder sink).

5.2 Real Engine Efficiencies and Their Implications for Φ

Real engines fall short of Carnot due to irreversibilities: friction, heat loss, imperfect combustion, material limits. The gap between theoretical and actual efficiency represents wasted energy—energy that could have powered computation.

Engine type $T_H$ (°C) Carnot (%) Actual (%) Fraction of Carnot Wasted energy fraction
Coal plant (subcritical) 540 63 35 0.56 0.44
Coal plant (supercritical) 600 66 42 0.64 0.36
Combined cycle gas turbine 1500 83 60 0.72 0.28
Nuclear PWR 315 50 32 0.64 0.36
Automobile gasoline 1000 77 25 0.32 0.68
Diesel engine 800 72 35 0.49 0.51

Critical observation: Transportation engines (automobiles, diesel) operate at particularly low fractions of Carnot because of size, cost, and duty cycle constraints. This represents a massive waste of exergy—approximately 65-75% of fuel energy is rejected as heat.

From the perspective of Φ, every joule wasted is a joule that cannot be used for computation. Improving heat engine efficiency is therefore equivalent to increasing the energy available for information processing, holding fuel input constant.

5.3 The Temperature Constraint: Materials Limit T_H

Why don't we simply raise $T_H$ to approach Carnot = 1? Because materials fail at high temperatures.

The maximum operating temperature of a turbine blade is limited by:

· Creep: Slow deformation under stress at high temperature
· Oxidation: Chemical reaction with combustion products
· Melting: Obvious phase change limit

Advanced superalloys (nickel-based, with refractory elements) operate at ~1100°C in the hottest sections of gas turbines. Ceramic matrix composites (CMCs) promise 1300-1400°C. Each 100°C increase in turbine inlet temperature yields approximately 5-10% improvement in efficiency.

Thesis implication: The trajectory toward higher Φ through improved energy efficiency is partly a materials science problem. The same material constraints that limit turbine temperatures also limit semiconductor performance (thermal conductivity, reliability). Advances in materials benefit both energy and information technologies simultaneously—a convergence we will explore in Part VI.

5.4 Cogeneration: Extracting More Φ from the Same Fuel

Cogeneration (combined heat and power, CHP) captures waste heat for useful purposes—industrial processes, district heating, absorption cooling. This raises total fuel utilization to 80-90%, even if electrical efficiency remains modest.

The effective Φ of a cogeneration system is:

\Phi_{\text{CHP}} = \frac{E_{\text{electric}} \times \Phi_{\text{electric}} + E_{\text{thermal}} \times \Phi_{\text{thermal}}}{E_{\text{fuel}}}

where $\Phi_{\text{thermal}}$ is the information value of thermal energy (low, since heat directly powers little computation). However, if waste heat enables processes that would otherwise require separate energy input, the net effect is to free up more high-quality energy for computation.

Consider a data center: servers generate waste heat. If this heat is used for building heating or absorption cooling, the net energy required for computing decreases, effectively increasing $\Phi$ for the system.

5.5 Combined Cycle: The Pinnacle of Thermal Efficiency

The most efficient thermal power plants combine two cycles:

1. Brayton cycle (gas turbine): Air compressed, fuel burned, hot gas expands through turbine. Exhaust at 500-600°C.
2. Rankine cycle (steam turbine): Exhaust heat generates steam, which drives a second turbine.

Overall efficiency:

\eta_{\text{combined}} = \eta_{\text{gas}} + (1 - \eta_{\text{gas}})\eta_{\text{steam}}

With $\eta_{\text{gas}} \approx 40\%$ and $\eta_{\text{steam}} \approx 35\%$, overall $\eta \approx 60\%$—the highest of any thermal power plant.

Implication: The limit of thermal-to-electrical conversion is approximately 60-65% with current materials. To exceed this, we would need:

· Higher turbine inlet temperatures (requiring better materials)
· Alternative cycles (e.g., supercritical CO₂, which may achieve 50-55% at lower temperatures)
· Direct conversion (thermoelectric, thermionic, magnetohydrodynamic)—but these have their own limits

The 60-65% ceiling means that even with perfect heat engines, approximately 35-40% of primary energy in thermal plants is rejected as low-temperature heat. This is unavoidable—a consequence of the second law.

5.6 Heat Engines and the Civilizational Metabolic Rate

What do heat engines contribute to $\mathcal{M}$? They convert primary energy (chemical, nuclear) into electricity, which then powers computation. The chain is:

E_{\text{primary}} \xrightarrow{\eta_{\text{thermal}}} E_{\text{electric}} \xrightarrow{\Phi_{\text{computing}}} \text{bits}

The effective $\Phi$ of primary energy is:

\Phi_{\text{primary}} = \eta_{\text{thermal}} \times \Phi_{\text{computing}}

If $\Phi_{\text{computing}} = 10^{12}$ bits/J and $\eta_{\text{thermal}} = 0.6$, then $\Phi_{\text{primary}} = 6 \times 10^{11}$ bits/J—a factor of 0.6 reduction.

Thesis implication: Improving heat engine efficiency is equivalent to improving the effective Φ of primary energy. Each percentage point gain in $\eta_{\text{thermal}}$ increases civilization's information-processing capacity by the same percentage, holding primary energy constant. This is why efficiency improvements are as valuable as new sources.

