Chapter 7 — Renewable Energy: The Intermittent Path

7.1 The Solar Inheritance

All renewable energy (except geothermal and tidal) derives ultimately from the Sun. The solar constant:

S \approx 1361 \text{ W/m}^2

Total solar power intercepted by Earth: $\pi R^2 \times S \approx 1.74 \times 10^{17}$ W. This is approximately 10,000 times current human energy consumption.

Thesis implication: There is no fundamental energy shortage. The challenge is concentration, conversion, and temporal matching. Solar provides enough energy to support Kardashev Type I civilization (10¹⁶ W)—approximately 1000× current consumption. The limits are technological and economic, not physical.

7.2 Photovoltaic Conversion and the Shockley-Queisser Limit

Photovoltaic cells convert photons directly to electricity. The maximum efficiency for a single-junction cell is given by the Shockley-Queisser limit:

\eta_{\text{SQ}} \approx 33\% \text{ for band gap } \approx 1.34 \text{ eV}

This limit arises from:

· Below-bandgap photons not absorbed (transmission loss)
· Above-bandgap photons thermalizing excess energy to band edge (thermalization loss)
· Radiative recombination (fundamental)
· Thermodynamic factors (angle, concentration)

Multi-junction cells stack materials with different bandgaps, each absorbing a slice of the spectrum. Theoretical efficiency for infinite junctions approaches the Carnot limit for solar conversion (~86% under full concentration).

Real efficiencies:

Technology Efficiency (lab) Efficiency (commercial) Bandgap (eV)
Crystalline silicon 26.7% 18-22% 1.12
Perovskite 25.7% ~18% (emerging) Tunable 1.2-2.3
GaAs 29.1% ~25% (space) 1.42
Multi-junction (III-V) 47.1% ~40% (concentrator) Multiple
Thin film (CdTe) 22.1% 17-19% 1.45

Contribution to Φ: Solar PV generates electricity directly, with no moving parts, at distributed scales. Its $\Phi_{\text{contribution}}$ is:

\Phi_{\text{PV}} = \frac{\text{Electricity generated}}{\text{Embodied energy}} \times \Phi_{\text{computing}} \times \eta_{\text{balance}}

The key metric is Energy Payback Time (EPBT)—the time to generate the energy embodied in manufacturing. For modern PV, EPBT is 1-3 years, depending on location. Over a 30-year lifetime, EROI is 10-30:1—comparable to current fossil fuels.

7.3 Wind Power and the Betz Limit

Wind turbines extract kinetic energy from moving air. The maximum theoretical efficiency is the Betz limit:

C_{P,\max} = \frac{16}{27} \approx 59.3\%

This arises from conservation of mass and momentum: the wind must retain sufficient kinetic energy to exit the turbine.

Real turbines achieve $C_P \approx 40-50\%$. Power scales with wind speed cubed:

P = \frac{1}{2} \rho A v^3 C_P

This cubic dependence means siting is critical: doubling wind speed increases power 8×.

Capacity factor: Wind turbines typically achieve 30-45% capacity factor (average power/rated power) in good locations, compared to 15-25% for solar PV. This means wind is more "firm" but still variable.

7.4 The Intermittency Challenge

The fundamental challenge of renewables is temporal mismatch between supply and demand.

Solar variability:

· Diurnal: zero at night, peak at noon
· Seasonal: varies with latitude (winter/summer)
· Weather: clouds can reduce output 50-90% in minutes

Wind variability:

· Weather-dependent: lulls and gusts
· Seasonal: typically stronger in winter
· Geographic: correlated across regions (weather systems)

For an autonomous AI requiring continuous power, intermittency must be managed through:

Overcapacity: Build 3-4× peak demand, curtail when excess. This raises cost but provides reliability.

Geographic smoothing: Connect distant sites. Wind in different regions decorrelates over ~500 km; solar over time zones.

Storage: The essential solution for high-penetration renewables.

Demand response: Shift computation to times of surplus. This is natural for batch processing but challenging for real-time AI.

7.5 The Storage Requirement for Autonomous AI

Consider an AI requiring constant power $P_{\text{AI}}$. With solar-only generation at latitude 40°N, the worst-case winter period might have 5 days of low insolation (clouds + short days). Storage required:

S_{\text{req}} = P_{\text{AI}} \times t_{\text{autonomy}} \times \frac{1}{\eta_{\text{round-trip}}}

For $P_{\text{AI}} = 20$ MW (data center scale) and $t = 5$ days = 120 hours:

S_{\text{req}} = 20 \times 10^6 \times 120 \times 3600 \times \frac{1}{0.85} \approx 1.02 \times 10^{13} \text{ J} \approx 2.8 \text{ GWh}

At current lithium-ion costs ($150/kWh), this storage costs $420 million—significant but not prohibitive for a nation-state or major corporation.

Thesis implication: Intermittency is a solvable engineering problem, not a fundamental barrier to autonomous AI. The cost of storage adds to the total cost of Φ, but as storage costs decline (learning rate ~15-20% per doubling of cumulative production), this barrier diminishes.

7.6 The EROI Transition

The transition from fossil fuels (EROI 15-30:1 currently) to renewables (EROI 10-20:1) represents a modest decline in energy surplus. The surplus fraction:

f_{\text{surplus}} = 1 - \frac{1}{\text{EROI}}

For EROI = 30: $f = 0.967$ (3.3% of energy used for energy sector)
For EROI = 15: $f = 0.933$ (6.7% used for energy sector)
For EROI = 10: $f = 0.900$ (10% used for energy sector)

The declining surplus means less energy available for non-energy activities—including computation. To maintain $\mathcal{M}$ growth, Φ must improve fast enough to compensate:

\frac{d\mathcal{M}}{dt} = \mathcal{M}\left(\frac{1}{E}\frac{dE}{dt} + \frac{1}{\Phi}\frac{d\Phi}{dt}\right)

If $\frac{1}{E}\frac{dE}{dt}$ becomes negative (energy contraction), we require $\frac{1}{\Phi}\frac{d\Phi}{dt} > |\frac{1}{E}\frac{dE}{dt}|$.

Historical Φ improvement (Koomey's Law) has been ~60%/year, far exceeding any plausible energy contraction. The risk is that Φ improvement slows to <2-3%/year as physical limits approach, while energy supply stagnates or declines due to EROI constraints.

