10.2 The Minimum Energy for Human-Level AI

What energy is required to support human-level artificial intelligence? Two approaches:

Biological analogy: Human brain consumes ~20 W for ~10¹⁶ bit operations/s → Φ ≈ 5 × 10¹⁴ bits/J.

If we achieve this Φ with artificial systems, power for human-level AI is:

P_{\text{human-level}} = \frac{10^{16} \text{ ops/s}}{5 \times 10^{14} \text{ ops/J}} = 20 \text{ W}

Exactly the same as a human brain. This suggests that if we can match biological efficiency, the energy cost of human-level AI is negligible—a few watts per brain-equivalent.

Current AI practice: Large language models require:

· Training: 10²³-10²⁵ FLOP (10⁸-10¹⁰ kWh)
· Inference: ~10¹² FLOP per query → ~0.1-1 kWh per query at current efficiency

At current Φ (~10¹² bits/J), a human-equivalent AI (10¹⁶ ops/s) would require:

P = \frac{10^{16}}{10^{12}} = 10^4 \text{ W} = 10 \text{ kW}

Still modest—about the power consumption of a large home.

Thesis implication: The energy cost of human-level AI is not a barrier. Even at current efficiencies, a single human-equivalent AI consumes no more than a typical household. The barrier is not energy per AI but the total compute required for training and the coordination of many AIs.

10.3 The Energy Cost of Superintelligence

Superintelligence implies capability exceeding all human brains combined. There are approximately 8 billion humans, each with ~10¹⁶ ops/s brain capacity, giving total human cognitive throughput:

C_{\text{humanity}} \approx 8 \times 10^9 \times 10^{16} = 8 \times 10^{25} \text{ ops/s}

To match this with artificial systems at Φ = 10¹³ bits/J (approaching biological):

P = \frac{8 \times 10^{25}}{10^{13}} = 8 \times 10^{12} \text{ W} = 8 \text{ TW}

This is approximately half of current global primary energy consumption (~18 TW). A superintelligence matching all human brains would require ~40% of current global energy.

To exceed humanity by a factor of 1000 (a plausible superintelligence threshold):

P = 8 \times 10^{15} \text{ W} = 8000 \text{ TW}

This exceeds current global energy by a factor of ~400—requiring Kardashev Type I scale (~10¹⁶ W).

Critical conclusion: Superintelligence at significant multiples of human cognitive capacity requires energy at civilizational or planetary scales. This is the ultimate link between energy technology and the trajectory toward autonomy: the physical limits to superintelligence are energy limits.

10.4 The Convergence: Nuclear + AI

The only known energy sources capable of supplying 10¹⁶ W (Kardashev I) are:

· Solar: Requires covering ~1-2 million km² with collectors (area roughly the size of Mexico or Saudi Arabia). Technically possible but enormous land use and materials requirements.
· Fission: Requires ~10,000 1 GWe reactors. Feasible with existing technology (currently ~440 operating worldwide). Fuel availability: uranium in seawater is ~4.5 billion tons, sufficient for thousands of years at this scale.
· Fusion: If achieved, would require similar reactor count with cheaper fuel.

Thesis implication: The trajectory toward superintelligence inevitably leads to nuclear energy. Solar could theoretically suffice, but the land use and intermittency challenges at 10¹⁶ W scale are immense. Nuclear (fission or fusion) is the only demonstrated or plausible path to the energy densities required.

10.5 The Temporal Constraint: When Will Energy Bind?

Current global energy consumption: ~18 TW, growing at ~2%/year. At this rate:

E(t) = E_0 e^{rt}, \quad r = 0.02

Time to reach 10¹⁶ W (Kardashev I):

t = \frac{\ln(10^{16}/2 \times 10^{13})}{0.02} = \frac{\ln(500)}{0.02} \approx \frac{6.2}{0.02} \approx 310 \text{ years}

If Φ improves at 10%/year (slower than historical but plausible post-Moore), time to superintelligence at current energy is:

\Phi(t) = \Phi_0 e^{rt}, \quad r = 0.10

To achieve 1000× human cognitive capacity with current energy:

\frac{8 \times 10^{25} \times 1000}{E_{\text{current}} \times \Phi(t)} = 1

Solving:

\Phi(t) = \frac{8 \times 10^{28}}{2 \times 10^{13} \times 10^{12} \text{ (convert W to J/s?)}}

Need careful unit analysis, but the point is: Φ improvement can substitute for energy growth, but only up to physical limits (Landauer). At Landauer limit, Φ_max ≈ 3 × 10¹⁴ bits/J at 300K. At this Φ, power required for 1000× human capacity:

P = \frac{8 \times 10^{28} \text{ ops/s}}{3 \times 10^{14} \text{ ops/J}} \approx 2.7 \times 10^{14} \text{ W} \approx 270 \text{ TW}

This is ~15× current global energy—achievable within centuries at 2% growth, or much sooner with dedicated build-out.

Final implication: The trajectory toward superintelligence is not energy-constrained in the near term. Even at fundamental physical limits, the energy required for massive superintelligence is within reach of a determined civilization. The binding constraints are not physical but political, economic, and—most critically—alignmmental.

