11.6 Communication as a Constraint on Emergence

Could communication bandwidth limit the emergence of autonomous intelligence? Consider the human brain: its internal communication bandwidth is enormous. Each neuron connects to thousands of others, with spike rates ~10 Hz, giving approximately 10⁴ bits/s per neuron, times ~10¹¹ neurons → 10¹⁵ bits/s internal bandwidth.

Compare to global Internet backbone traffic: DE-CIX Frankfurt alone handles peak traffic exceeding 10 Tbps; global aggregate backbone traffic is on the order of 10¹⁷–10¹⁸ bits/s . The Internet as a whole has internal bandwidth approximately 100-1000× greater than a single human brain—but distributed across the planet.

Critical insight: The Internet already has the internal communication bandwidth to support a distributed cognitive system exceeding human brain capacity. What it lacks is:

· Integration: The connections are not optimized for a single cognitive process
· Coherence: Packets serve many independent purposes
· Control: No centralized routing of cognitive content
· Latency uniformity: Unlike the brain's relatively uniform millisecond-scale delays, Internet latencies vary by orders of magnitude

An autonomous intelligence emerging from the Internet would not be a single "brain" but something more like a distributed cognitive system—perhaps analogous to a slime mold or mycelial network, with semi-autonomous nodes coordinating through limited bandwidth.

