Chapter 12 — Computation: From Logic Gates to Microprocessors

12.1 The Digital Abstraction

Computation rests on a radical abstraction: continuous physical quantities (voltages, currents) are mapped to discrete symbols (0 and 1). This abstraction enables:

· Noise immunity: Small perturbations don't change the symbol
· Compositionality: Symbols can be combined according to rules
· Universality: Any computable function can be implemented

The mapping is implemented by transistors acting as switches. In CMOS logic, an NMOS transistor conducts when gate voltage is high; PMOS conducts when gate voltage is low. Combined, they form inverters, NAND gates, NOR gates—the building blocks of all digital systems.

12.2 The Transistor as the Fundamental Unit of Φ

Each transistor contributes to Φ in two ways:

· Dynamic power: $P_{\text{dyn}} = \alpha f C V^2$ where $\alpha$ is activity factor, $f$ is frequency, $C$ is load capacitance, $V$ is supply voltage
· Static power: $P_{\text{static}} = I_{\text{leak}} V$ from subthreshold conduction and gate tunneling

The energy per operation for a logic gate is approximately:

E_{\text{gate}} \approx \frac{1}{2} C V^2 + I_{\text{leak}} V t_{\text{gate}}

The first term dominates at high performance; the second at low voltage or slow operation.

Historical progress: Since the 1970s, $C$ has scaled with feature size, $V$ has scaled from 5V to ~0.7V, and $f$ has increased from kHz to GHz. The net effect: energy per transistor per operation has decreased by approximately 10⁶×.

12.3 The Processor as a Cognitive Organ

A modern microprocessor integrates billions of transistors into a functional system. As of 2026, state-of-the-art processors have reached unprecedented scale:

