Implication for autonomous intelligence: The memory hierarchy imposes a fundamental trade-off between speed and capacity. An AI that needs rapid access to vast knowledge must either:

· Store it in fast memory (expensive, power-hungry)
· Tolerate latency (slowing cognition)
· Or design algorithms that work with compressed representations

The human brain solves this with massive parallelism and content-addressable memory. Neuromorphic computing aims to replicate these features.

