Chapter 13 — Moore's Law and the Limits of Scaling: The Engine of Φ

13.1 Moore's Law as a Self-Fulfilling Prophecy

Moore's Law—the observation that transistor density doubles approximately every two years—became a self-fulfilling prophecy driving the semiconductor industry.

N(t) = N_0 2^{(t-t_0)/\tau}, \quad \tau \approx 2 \text{ years}

From the Intel 4004 (2,300 transistors, 1971) to Nvidia's Vera Rubin (336 billion transistors, 2026), this represents a factor of approximately 146 million× increase in density .

Contribution to Φ: Density enables:

· More parallelism (more transistors working simultaneously)
· Lower cost per transistor (enabling more total compute for same budget)
· Shorter interconnects (reducing capacitance and energy)

The relationship between density and Φ is:

\Phi \propto \frac{\text{Transistors} \times \text{Frequency}}{\text{Power}}

Under Dennard scaling, frequency increased with density, power per transistor decreased, and Φ improved dramatically.

13.2 Koomey's Law: The Direct Measurement of Φ Progress

Koomey's Law tracks the metric we care about directly: computations per joule.

\Phi(t) = \Phi_0 2^{(t-t_0)/\tau_{\Phi}}, \quad \tau_{\Phi} \approx 1.5 \text{ years (historically)}

This doubling every 1.5 years means Φ improves by a factor of 100 every decade. Over 50 years (1970-2020), Φ improved by approximately 10⁵×.

