Chapter 18 — Neural Networks and Deep Learning: The Dominant Paradigm

18.1 The Artificial Neuron

The perceptron (Rosenblatt, 1958) remains the fundamental building block:

y = \phi\left(\sum_i w_i x_i + b\right)

where \phi is an activation function introducing nonlinearity:

Activation Formula Properties
Sigmoid \sigma(z) = 1/(1+e^{-z}) Smooth, bounded, vanishing gradient
Tanh \tanh(z) Zero-centered, still vanishing gradient
ReLU \max(0, z) Sparse, non-vanishing gradient, dying neurons
Leaky ReLU \max(\alpha z, z) Addresses dying ReLU
GELU z \Phi(z) Smooth ReLU approximation, used in transformers
Swish z \sigma(z) Self-gated, used in modern architectures

Universal approximation theorem: A network with one hidden layer can approximate any continuous function given sufficient width. Depth, however, enables compositionality—building complex functions from simpler ones—and dramatically improves sample efficiency.

18.2 Architectures: From Convnets to Transformers

Convolutional neural networks (CNNs) revolutionized computer vision by exploiting spatial locality:

· Local connectivity: Each neuron connects to a small region
· Weight sharing: Same filters applied across space
· Pooling: Downsampling for translation invariance

Residual networks (ResNet) solved the degradation problem—where deeper networks became harder to optimize (He et al., 2015). The residual block:

y = F(x, \{W_i\}) + x

This formulation makes it easier to learn identity mappings, enabling networks with hundreds of layers. ResNet-152 demonstrated that extreme depth could be effectively trained.

Dense networks (DenseNet) (Huang et al., 2017) took connectivity further: each layer receives inputs from all preceding layers via concatenation:

x_\ell = H_\ell([x_0, x_1, \dots, x_{\ell-1}])

This maximizes information flow, improves gradient propagation, and enables parameter efficiency through feature reuse. DenseNets achieve comparable accuracy to ResNets with significantly fewer parameters.

MobileNets (Howard et al., 2017) prioritize computational efficiency through depthwise separable convolutions, factorizing standard convolutions into:

· Depthwise convolution: Single filter per input channel
· Pointwise convolution: 1 \times 1 convolution to combine channels

This reduces computation by approximately 8-9\times for 3 \times 3 kernels, enabling on-device AI. Width multiplier \alpha and resolution multiplier \rho allow continuous efficiency-accuracy trade-offs.

18.3 The Transformer Revolution

The transformer architecture (Vaswani et al., 2017) has become the dominant paradigm for AI, underpinning all major language models including GPT-4, GPT-5, Gemini, Claude, and Llama (Clarifai, Nov 2025).

Core innovation: Self-attention

\text{Attention}(Q, K, V) = \text{softmax}\left(\frac{QK^T}{\sqrt{d_k}}\right)V

Each token attends to all others, allowing the model to capture long-range dependencies without the sequential bottleneck of RNNs. Multi-head attention runs multiple attention mechanisms in parallel, enabling the model to focus on different types of relationships.

Key components:

· Positional encodings: Inject sequence order information
· Layer normalization: Stabilize training
· Feed-forward networks: Apply same MLP to each position
· Residual connections: Enable deep stacks
· Causal masking: For autoregressive generation

Scaling transformers: The architecture's clean design scales remarkably well. GPT-3 (175B parameters) demonstrated that larger models develop new capabilities. GPT-4 and GPT-5 extended this trend, with rumored parameter counts exceeding 1 trillion (Clarifai, Nov 2025).

18.4 Training Deep Networks

Backpropagation computes gradients via the chain rule:

\frac{\partial L}{\partial w_{ij}^{(l)}} = \frac{\partial L}{\partial a_j^{(l)}} \frac{\partial a_j^{(l)}}{\partial w_{ij}^{(l)}}

where a_j^{(l)} is pre-activation at layer l. Error propagates backward through the network.

Optimization challenges:

Challenge Description Mitigation
Vanishing gradients Gradients become very small in deep networks Residual connections, normalization, ReLU
Exploding gradients Gradients become very large Gradient clipping, normalization
Saddle points Many directions have zero gradient Momentum, adaptive methods
Ill-conditioning Different directions have very different curvature Adaptive learning rates
Local minima In high dimensions, most critical points are saddle points Overparameterization helps

Optimizers:

· SGD with momentum: Accelerates convergence
· Adam: Adaptive moment estimation, default for transformers
· AdamW: Adam with decoupled weight decay
· Sophia: Newer optimizer with better scaling properties

18.5 The 2026 Landscape: Reasoning-Focused Post-Training

As of March 2026, the focus has shifted from raw model scaling to reasoning-focused post-training (TWIML Podcast #762, Feb 2026). Sebastian Raschka, independent LLM researcher, notes that methods like self-consistency, self-refinement, and verifiable-reward reinforcement learning have become central to progress in domains like mathematics and coding.

Key techniques:

· Chain-of-thought prompting: Models generate intermediate reasoning steps
· Self-consistency: Sample multiple reasoning paths and take majority vote
· Self-refinement: Models critique and improve their own outputs
· Verifiable-reward RL: Reinforcement learning with objective correctness signals (e.g., math problems with verifiable answers)

These techniques leverage inference-time compute rather than training-time compute—a fundamental shift that allows models to "think longer" about hard problems. Frontier GPT-5 series models (e.g., the o-series reasoning variants) demonstrate 15× faster generation with 128K context, optimized for real-time coding tasks (OpenAI blog, Feb 2026; Clarifai, Nov 2025).

18.6 Efficiency and Edge Deployment

The drive toward efficiency has produced specialized architectures and techniques:

· Mixture-of-experts (MoE) : Sparsely activated models where each token routes to a subset of "expert" modules. Mistral Large 2 uses this architecture to provide strong performance at competitive cost (Clarifai, Nov 2025).
· Quantization: Reducing numerical precision from 32-bit to 16-bit, 8-bit, or 4-bit. However, Han et al. (2026) identified a "quantization trap" in multi-hop reasoning: reducing precision from 16-bit to 8/4-bit can paradoxically increase net energy consumption while degrading reasoning accuracy due to hardware casting overhead and dequantization kernel latency (Han et al., arXiv:2602.13595, Feb 2026).
· Edge AI: Lightweight models like Gemini Nano bring powerful capabilities to smartphones and IoT devices. The sub-20M parameter regime—TinyML—has revealed unique scaling behaviors: error exponents are 1.4-2× steeper than large models, but saturation occurs earlier (Alnemari et al., arXiv:2603.07365, March 2026).

