Chapter 19 — Scaling Laws: The Predictable Path to Intelligence

19.1 Empirical Scaling Laws

Kaplan et al. (2020) established that language model performance follows power laws with model size, dataset size, and compute:

L(N) \approx \left(\frac{N_c}{N}\right)^{\alpha_N}, \quad \alpha_N \approx 0.076

L(D) \approx \left(\frac{D_c}{D}\right)^{\alpha_D}, \quad \alpha_D \approx 0.095

L(C) \approx \left(\frac{C_c}{C}\right)^{\alpha_C}, \quad \alpha_C \approx 0.050

These laws imply diminishing returns: to halve error, you need:

· 11× more parameters, or
· 8× more data, or
· 16× more compute

19.2 Chinchilla Scaling: Optimal Allocation

Hoffmann et al. (2022) discovered that many large models were undertrained—they could achieve the same performance with smaller models and more data. For optimal training:

N_{\text{opt}} \propto C^{1/2}, \quad D_{\text{opt}} \propto C^{1/2}

This means that when increasing compute budget, you should scale model size and data proportionally. Violating this wastes compute—a lesson that shaped subsequent model development.

19.3 Theoretical Foundations (2026)

Yang et al. (2026) provided the first rigorous theoretical derivation of scaling laws for transformers (Yang et al., arXiv:2512.22088v2, Jan 2026). Their analysis unifies learning dynamics and generalization, establishing a two-stage upper bound on expected risk:

1. Compute-starved phase: Excess risk decays exponentially with computational cost \mathsf{C}
2. Data-limited phase: After a critical threshold, generalization error follows a power-law decay of \Theta(\mathsf{C}^{-1/6})

This phase transition occurs when:

\mathsf{C} \propto \mathsf{N}^3 \quad \text{(simplified critical condition)}

The theoretical bound matches empirical observations: initially rapid improvement, then diminishing returns as data constraints dominate.

19.4 Scaling in the Tiny Regime

Alnemari et al. (2026) examined the sub-20M parameter regime—where TinyML and edge AI operate (Alnemari et al., arXiv:2603.07365, March 2026). Training 90 models from 22K to 19.8M parameters on CIFAR-100, they found:

· Steeper exponents: \alpha = 0.156 (ScaleCNN) and \alpha = 0.106 (MobileNetV2)—1.4-2× steeper than large language models
· Local exponent decay: Power law does not hold uniformly; local exponents decay with scale
· Saturation: MobileNetV2 saturates at 19.8M parameters (\alpha_{\text{local}} = 0.006)
· Error structure changes: Jaccard overlap between smallest and largest models is only 0.35—compression changes which inputs are misclassified, not merely how many
· Calibration: Smallest models are best calibrated (ECE = 0.013 vs. peak 0.110 at mid-size)

Critical implication: Aggregate accuracy is misleading for edge deployment. Validation must happen at target model size—small models don't just make more errors; they make different errors.

19.5 The Quantization Trap: Breaking Linear Scaling

A fundamental assumption has been that reducing numerical precision linearly improves efficiency. Han et al. (2026) demonstrated that this scaling law breaks for multi-hop reasoning (Han et al., arXiv:2602.13595, Feb 2026).

Reducing precision from 16-bit to 8/4-bit can:

· Increase net energy consumption
· Degrade reasoning accuracy
· Create a "quantization trap"

Theoretical decomposition reveals two causes:

1. Hardware casting overhead: Hidden latency of dequantization kernels becomes a dominant bottleneck in sequential reasoning chains
2. Sequential energy amortization failure: The expected linear savings don't materialize due to irregular memory access patterns

Thesis implication: The path to efficient intelligence is not simply "smaller is better." Complex reasoning requires maintaining precision through sequential operations—a finding with profound implications for autonomous systems that must reason over multiple steps.

19.6 Beyond Scaling: The Bitter Lesson

Rich Sutton's (2019) "bitter lesson" remains relevant: general methods that leverage computation (search, learning) outperform human-engineered knowledge in the long run. Scaling compute beats specialized algorithms.

But 2026 reveals a more nuanced picture:

Approach Strengths Weaknesses 2026 Status
Raw scaling Predictable improvement, emergent capabilities Diminishing returns, data limits Continuing but slowing
Reasoning post-training Better performance per compute, inference-time scaling Not fully understood, task-specific Rapidly advancing (TWIML #762)
Specialized architectures Efficiency gains, edge deployment Narrower capabilities Maturing
Neuro-symbolic Interpretability, reasoning Scaling challenges Active research
Test-time compute Dynamic allocation, adaptivity Latency, cost Growing importance

Critical observation: The bitter lesson may itself be subject to diminishing returns. As we approach physical limits (Landauer, data availability), the returns to raw scaling diminish, and algorithmic innovation becomes relatively more valuable.

