Chapter 23 — Genetic Engineering: Reading and Writing the Code of Life

23.1 DNA as Information Storage

From Volume IV (Biology), we recall that DNA is nature's information storage medium. The genetic code maps nucleotide triplets (codons) to amino acids, enabling the synthesis of proteins—the molecular machines that execute life's functions.

The information density of DNA is extraordinary:

Storage Medium Volumetric Density (bits/cm³) Persistence Energy per access
DNA (theoretical) 10^{19} Thousands of years (frozen) High (sequencing/synthesis)
Flash memory 10^{13} Decades Low
Hard disk drive 10^{12} Decades Low
Magnetic tape 10^{10} Decades High

Critical observation: A single gram of DNA could theoretically store all human knowledge—approximately 10^{21} bits—with room to spare. The challenge is not density but read/w speed: sequencing and synthesis remain slow and expensive compared to electronic memory.

23.2 Reading DNA: Sequencing Technologies

DNA sequencing—determining the order of nucleotides in a DNA molecule—has advanced with Moore-like exponential growth.

Generation Technology Read Length Throughput per run Error Rate Cost per Genome (2026)
