Third (Oxford Nanopore) Nanopore current sensing 100 kb+ 10-100 Gb 5-15% (raw) ~$500
Emerging (2026) AI-enhanced basecalling Variable Increasing <1% after correction Projected <$100

AI's role: Modern basecalling—converting raw sensor data to nucleotide sequences—increasingly uses neural networks. Oxford Nanopore's Bonito and similar tools employ deep learning to improve accuracy, especially in homopolymer regions and modified base detection. As of March 2026, AI-enhanced sequencing achieves raw error rates below 5% with computational correction approaching 99.9% accuracy (nanoporetech.com, 2026).

23.3 Writing DNA: Synthesis Technologies

DNA synthesis—constructing arbitrary sequences from nucleotides—has seen even more dramatic cost reduction.

