Enzymatic synthesis: Traditional chemical synthesis (phosphoramidite) is being supplemented by enzymatic methods using terminal deoxynucleotidyl transferase (TdT). Enzymatic synthesis offers:

· Longer fragments (500+ bases vs. 200 for chemical)
· Lower error rates
· Potential for in situ synthesis within cells

DNA writing speed: Current synthesis platforms can produce millions of oligonucleotides in parallel on microarrays, enabling large-scale gene synthesis and assembly. Twist Bioscience, Ginkgo Bioworks, and others operate industrial-scale foundries.

23.4 CRISPR-Cas9: The Breakthrough Editor

CRISPR-Cas9, adapted from bacterial immune systems, has revolutionized genetic engineering. The system uses:

· Guide RNA (gRNA) : 20-nucleotide sequence complementary to target DNA
· Cas9 nuclease: Creates double-strand break at target site

After cleavage, cellular repair mechanisms enable editing:

· Non-homologous end joining (NHEJ) : Error-prone repair, disrupts gene (knockout)
· Homology-directed repair (HDR) : Uses donor template to insert new sequence (knock-in)

2026 refinements:

Variant Modification Application
Cas9 nickase Cuts one strand only Reduces off-target effects
dCas9 (dead) No cutting, DNA binding only Gene regulation (CRISPRi/a)
Base editors Chemically convert bases without cutting C→T, A→G conversions
Prime editors Cas9 nickase + reverse transcriptase Precise sequence replacement
CRISPR-Cas12a Different PAM site, staggered cuts Expanded targeting

Off-target effects: The primary safety concern. Guide RNA design tools now incorporate deep learning models trained on thousands of empirical measurements to predict and minimize off-target activity. In vivo delivery remains challenging—viral vectors (AAV, lentivirus), lipid nanoparticles (LNPs), and virus-like particles (VLPs) each have trade-offs in efficiency, cargo capacity, and immunogenicity.

