23.6 Germline Editing: The Red Line

Editing human embryos—germline editing—affects all future generations and remains ethically contentious and legally restricted in most jurisdictions.

Technical status: Several research groups have demonstrated germline editing in human embryos, primarily for basic research and to study early development. The 2018 He Jiankui incident—birth of gene-edited twins (CCR5 knockout for HIV resistance)—provoked international condemnation and clarified the need for governance.

Ethical concerns:

· Safety: Off-target effects, mosaicism (some cells edited, others not)
· Consent: Future generations cannot consent
· Equity: Access unequal, potential for eugenics
· Human dignity: Commodification of life

International consensus: Most countries prohibit germline editing for reproduction. Research is permitted in some jurisdictions under strict oversight. The International Commission on the Clinical Use of Human Germline Genome Editing (2020) concluded it would be "irresponsible" to proceed without broad societal consensus.

