24.2 The Synthetic Yeast Genome (Sc2.0)

The Sc2.0 project aims to synthesize all 16 yeast chromosomes (~12 Mbp)—the first synthetic eukaryotic genome.

Design features:

· Removed introns: Non-coding sequences excised (except those essential for regulation)
· Removed transposons: Mobile genetic elements deleted
· Removed subtelomeric repeats: Unstable regions simplified
· Added watermarks: PCR tags for identification
· Replaced stop codons: TAG → TAA throughout (to enable future recoding)
· Created "neochromosomes": Designed chromosomes for genome scrambling

Status (March 2026): All 16 individual chromosomes have been synthesized and validated. The final step—combining all synthetic chromosomes into a single fully synthetic yeast strain—is in progress. This will represent the first synthetic eukaryote.

Recoding for non-standard amino acids: By freeing up codons (e.g., all TAG stop codons replaced), Sc2.0 enables incorporation of non-standard amino acids into proteins—expanding the genetic code beyond the natural 20.

24.3 Genetic Circuits: Programming Cells

Synthetic biologists engineer logic circuits in cells, treating gene regulation as computation.

Foundational circuits:

Circuit Components Function
Toggle switch Two mutually repressing genes Bistable memory
Repressilator Three genes in negative feedback loop Oscillator (periodic expression)
AND gate Two inputs required for output Logical conjunction
Pulse generator Transient activation Timing circuits
Counter Sequential logic Record number of events

Dynamics: These circuits follow differential equations from Volume IV (Gene Regulatory Networks):

\frac{dm_i}{dt} = \alpha_i \cdot f\left(\sum_j w_{ij} p_j\right) - \beta_i m_i

\frac{dp_i}{dt} = \gamma_i m_i - \delta_i p_i

Where m_i and p_i are mRNA and protein concentrations, \alpha_i is transcription rate, \beta_i mRNA degradation, \gamma_i translation rate, \delta_i protein degradation, and f is a regulatory function (often Hill-type).

Scaling up: 2026 sees efforts toward "biocomputers"—integrated circuits with dozens of gates performing tasks like:

· Environmental sensing and response
· Metabolic pathway optimization
· Disease detection and treatment
· Programmable therapeutics

24.4 Xenobiology: Expanding the Chemical Basis of Life

Xenobiology creates life with alternative biochemistry—departing from the canonical DNA-RNA-protein framework.

Xeno-nucleic acids (XNAs) : Synthetic polymers with non-natural sugars:

XNA Sugar Properties
TNA Threose Simpler than ribose, plausible prebiotic
HNA Hexitol Nuclease resistant
FANA 2'-fluoro arabino Nuclease resistant, therapeutic potential
CeNA Cyclohexene Stable, information storage

XNAs can store and transmit genetic information; some can even evolve in vitro. This demonstrates that DNA/RNA are not unique—they are nature's solution, but not the only possible solution.

Expanded genetic alphabet: Natural DNA uses four bases (A, T, G, C). Synthetic biologists have created additional base pairs:

· d5SICS-dNaM (Romesberg lab): Hydrophobic base pair, orthogonal to natural system
· TPT3-NaM : Further optimized for replication
· Hachimoji (Benner lab): Eight-letter alphabet (four natural + four synthetic)

Unnatural amino acids: The genetic code specifies 20 amino acids. By engineering orthogonal tRNA/synthetase pairs, cells can incorporate non-standard amino acids (NSAAs) with novel chemical properties:

· Fluorescent amino acids
· Photocrosslinkers
· Post-translational modification mimics
· Metal-binding amino acids

Status 2026: Semi-synthetic organisms with expanded genetic alphabets and multiple NSAAs exist in research labs. The first commercial applications (e.g., therapeutic proteins with enhanced properties) are in development.

