Chapter 31 — Physical Limits and the End of Growth

31.1 Thermodynamic Limits

The second law imposes fundamental constraints.

Landauer limit: E_{\min} = k_B T \ln 2 per irreversible bit operation. At 300K, \Phi_{\max} \approx 3\times10^{14} bits/J. This is within a factor of 10 of the human brain—and within a factor of 30 of 2026's best AI hardware.

Implication: Irreversible classical computation cannot exceed this by more than an order of magnitude. To go beyond, we need:

· Reversible computing: Approaches Landauer limit from below, can exceed it in principle by recycling energy
· Quantum computing: Different paradigm, not directly comparable
· Lower temperatures: Reduce k_B T, but cooling costs energy

The Margolus-Levitin theorem: Maximum computation rate for a system with average energy E is 2E/\pi\hbar operations per second. This means that to increase speed, you must increase energy—no free lunch.

31.2 Information Limits

The Bekenstein bound relates information to energy and size:

I \leq \frac{2\pi R E}{\hbar c \ln 2}

For a 1 kg object of 0.1 m radius, this is approximately 10^{42} bits—far beyond current technology. This is not a practical limit for the foreseeable future.

The holographic principle suggests that the information in a volume is bounded by its surface area in Planck units. For Earth, this is about 10^{75} bits—effectively infinite for any conceivable civilization.

Implication: Information limits are not the binding constraint. We are nowhere near them.

31.3 Energy Limits

The total solar energy reaching Earth is 1.7\times10^{17} W. Kardashev Type I civilization would capture a significant fraction of this.

Energy source Potential Limitations
Solar 10^{16} W achievable with ~1M km² collectors Land use, materials, intermittency
Fission 10^{16} W requires ~10,000 1 GWe reactors Fuel (seawater uranium sufficient), waste, proliferation
Fusion 10^{16} W achievable if engineering solved Still experimental

Global primary energy consumption 2026: ~18 TW, growing at ~2%/year. At this rate, Kardashev I (10^{16} W) would take ~310 years. But AI-driven efficiency could slow growth, and breakthroughs could accelerate it.

